ing due to ALPNExtension, but maybe that's not necessary. I'm noticing that there could be a concern around the call site, where \\\\\\\"supported behavior through public API\\\\\\\" is referenced. If a fake `java.specification.version` is used, it might not behave normally and could be perceived negatively. I think I need to be cautious about how this could impact the overall implementation.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating Java support issues**\\\\n\\\\nI am looking into the JavaVersion property within the DK support context. It seems the environment simulation isn’t really a bug, but it hardcodes \\\\\\\"1.8\\\\\\\", which may not be acceptable. While the target is just Java 8, I’m contemplating whether to disclose the limitations honestly. There's an added public API test, but it only triggers with the obsolete ALPNExtension. The user wants improvements, and I need to clarify that tests weren’t run. I might note that class support relies on the obsolete JDK availability.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Assessing changes and tests**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering whether to remove certain changes due to coverage issues, but the tests could be improved from the placeholders, so I want to keep them. There's also a potential issue with an untracked metadata directory, which could be pre-existing and forbidden. We haven't touched it, so I should be careful. I’ll double-check the build.gradle file to ensure that I haven't inadvertently enabled any disallowed actions. Finally, I might need to inspect the metadata directory to avoid any accidental issues.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_99PmjSecNs1ndjF4Xj9dqmyL|fc_09934c5d992f21e6016a29e23c11148190a3bd6c6d4b7928ac\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"find metadata/org.apache.pekko/pekko-http-core_3/1.3.0 -maxdepth 3 -type f -print | head -20\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"oca/gpt-5.5\",